---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About - Bryan Jacinto"
  description="About Bryan Jacinto - writer, SEO strategist, and web dev learner with 8 years of experience."
>
  <section
    class="w-full"
    style="background-color: var(--section-bg-primary); margin-top: -88px;"
  >
    <div
      class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 sm:px-6 pt-16 pb-16 scroll-reveal initial-visible"
    >
      <h1 class="mb-4 text-center">About</h1>

      <article class="prose max-w-none scroll-reveal-item">
        <p>
          Hey there! Bryan here. This is my about section, so I won't get into
          much corpo stuff or be way too formal. That's boring!
        </p>

        <p>
          But okay, fine, here's a snapshot:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>8 years of experience (writing, SEO, content strategy)</li>
          <li>Worked with clients and agencies from the US, EMEA, and UK (some local too)</li>
          <li>
            Industries: B2B, SaaS, Ecommerce, Crypto, Health, Travel, Real
            Estate, Gaming, General News, Investing (a bit). Honestly, I can
            work with almost any industry or vertical, just give me enough time
            to research.
          </li>
          <li>Knows SEO</li>
          <li>
            Deep into AI: agents, automation, prompt engineering, building
            scalable systems
          </li>
          <li>I also do web dev on the side, hence this portfolio</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          Anyway, if you're still not convinced, you can check out my work
          <a href="/work" class="text-[var(--color-link)] hover:underline">here</a>.
          As cliche as it may sound, they do speak for themselves. But if
          you're here to learn about the true me, then proceed.
        </p>

        <p>
          Alright, let's start again. You can call me Bry. I'm from the
          beautiful coastal city of Legazpi, Philippines, born and raised.
        </p>

        <p>
          I have been writing stuff for almost 8 years. I guess you can call me
          a veteran by now, but that's cringe, and even I, to myself, know that
          I still have a lot to learn. A ton of SEO, dev, and of course
          refining the way I write. Like most people, I treat learning as a
          never-ending cycle. Emphasis on cycle, because you never truly stop
          learning something you are genuinely interested in and passionate
          about. Wait, I think I'm getting philosophical, but you get the
          point, right?
        </p>

        <p>
          So right now, I'm learning web dev with the help of AI tools while
          also sharpening my writing chops. One thing I really want to improve
          is my own style. Like, when you read something and you know me, you'll
          go "Oh, Bry wrote this!"
        </p>

        <p>
          With the emerging capabilities of AI and its ability to regurgitate
          words and sentences better than us humans (disclaimer: with proper
          guidance and insane hand holding), I am on a self-mission to develop
          a tone and style that no robot can easily replicate.
        </p>

        <p>
          I'll admit, I'm a big fan of AI. I use it all the time! But I feel
          like we're in a creative crisis. Most people are ditching their
          brain's ability to think and formulate coherent thoughts and just
          delegating everything to AI. They are reaching actual levels of
          stupidity. AI should be a tool, and I'm telling you, when used right,
          even in writing, it can elevate an output to greater heights.
        </p>

        <p>
          I mentioned that I've also been getting into web development, and I
          genuinely enjoy it. I've made a couple of tools, like scrapers and
          custom ones built for my own use, but I also have a ton of ideas I
          want to build out. It's really fun, and honestly that fun meter sits
          higher for web dev than it does for writing right now. I still love
          writing too, but maybe I've just been doing it so long that the thrill
          of making something appear from nothing keeps hitting different every
          time.
        </p>

        <p>
          Aside from all that, at some point in my life, I want to pursue
          teaching. That will be the final chapter of my pursuit of learning
          and acquiring knowledge: sharing it with people, hopefully those with
          the same drive and passion as me. If I can, I want to be a professor.
          It has always been my greatest dream.
        </p>

        <p>
          So, TLDR: Writer, SEO guy, AI nerd, and part-time web dev who just
          wants to keep learning things and eventually teach them to someone who
          actually cares.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style is:global>
  .scroll-reveal {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(30px);
    transition:
      opacity 0.4s ease-out,
      transform 0.4s ease-out;
  }

  .scroll-reveal.is-visible {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }

  .scroll-reveal-item {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(20px);
    transition:
      opacity 0.3s ease-out,
      transform 0.3s ease-out;
  }

  .scroll-reveal.is-visible .scroll-reveal-item {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }

  /* Elements visible on initial load */
  .initial-visible {
    opacity: 1 !important;
    transform: none !important;
  }
</style>

<script>
  const aboutObserver = new IntersectionObserver(
    (entries) => {
      entries.forEach((entry) => {
        if (entry.isIntersecting) {
          entry.target.classList.add("is-visible");
          aboutObserver.unobserve(entry.target);
        }
      });
    },
    {
      root: null,
      rootMargin: "0px 0px -80px 0px",
      threshold: 0.15,
    },
  );

  document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", () => {
    document
      .querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>(".scroll-reveal")
      .forEach((el) => aboutObserver.observe(el));
  });
</script>
